photo.title: 16th century full blind-stamped pigskin binding
photo.description: Binding: 16th-century full blind-tooled pig; central compartment of right board stamped with figure of Lucretia plunging a dagger into her heart above illegible motto; 2 lines of effaced ms. above central compartment; 3 raised bands on spine; brief title on spine; all edges red. [The pairing of Lucretia and Justice (see below) seems to be a reasonably common 16th-century binding trope. Cf. J.C.T Oates, A Catalogue of the Fifteenth-Century Printed Books in the University Library, Cambridge (Cambridge: Cambridge UP, 1954), p. 473 and W.H.J. Wheale, Bookbindings and Rubbings of Bindings in the National Art Library, South Kensington (London: HMSO, 1898), p. 44.] Penn Libraries call number: GC5 H4699 539o All images from this book

photo.title: Allegorical woodcut, with printed captions, representing Martin Luther and his wife Katharina on horseback leading their followers by the broad way into hell (cf. Matthew 7:13-14). Used by Melchior Lotter of Leipzig
photo.description: Allegorical woodcut, with printed captions, representing Martin Luther and his wife Katharina on horseback leading their followers by the broad way into hell (cf. Matthew 7:13-14). Used by Melchior Lotter of Leipzig. Note Luther's fly-swatter, used to keep off the flies accompanying the devil toward whom he rides (possibly Beelzebub, whose name is interpreted as Lord of the Flies; cf. Matthew 10:25 and 12:24ff). Compare also the image from another anti-Lutheran pamphlet in the comment below. Established heading: Lotter, Melchior,‏ ‎‡d ca. 1470-1549‏ Penn Libraries call number: GC5 H2743 530l All images from this book

photo.title: William Clavering-Cowper, 2nd Earl Cowper (1709-1764)
photo.description:
Bookplate picturing the arms of the Cowper/Cooper family (Argent, three martlets, a chief engrailed, gules, on the latter as many annulets or. Supporters: two bay horses, with tails docked, proper. Crest: on a wreath, a lion's gamb erected and erased, or, holding a branch, vert, fructed, gules.), with earl's coronet and motto "Tuum est," engraved by "Cole".

Several engravers named Cole were active in producing bookplates in the 18th century; cf. H.W. Fincham, Artists and Engravers of British and American Bookplates (London: Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co., 1897), p. 18ff. This is perhaps the work of M. Cole for Earl Cowper ca. 1730 -- that would be William Clavering-Cowper, 2nd Earl Cowper (1709-1764), who succeeded to the title in 1723. According to E. Hasted in The History and Topographical Survey of the County of Kent, 2nd ed., v. 9 (Canterbury: Bristow, 1800), p. 64, William "some time before [his death] prefixed the surname and arms of Clavering to his own, according to the will of his mother's brother" [i.e. John Clavering, 1698-1762]." This bookplate would predate that event. (The book to which it is affixed, Nummi Britannici Historia, or, An Historical Account of English Money was printed in London by W. Meadows in 1726.)

Penn Libraries call number: EC8 L4723 726n

photo.title: Ao. 1679 [illegible words] Matthaus Merian[?]
photo.description: This could be Merian, Matthäus, the Elder (1593–1650), a Swiss engraver and draftsman., who worked in Germany and produced numerous engravings of battles and hunts, and topographic prints of European towns. The inscription is dated 1679, but since part of it it's illegible, we can assume the inscription says the book was bought from him. Or it could be his son, Matthäus Merian, the younger, 1621–87, portrait and historical painter, worked throughout Europe. His dates would fit our inscription better. Both are established: Merian, Matthaeus,‏ ‎‡d 1593-1650‏ Merian, Matthaeus,‏ ‎‡d 1621-1687‏ Penn Libraries call number: IC5 P6964 En546h Folio All images from this book

photo.title: Tenth in a series of woodcut illustrations representing one of the ten ages of human life. Used by Hans Schobser of Munich
photo.description: Tenth in a series of 10 illustrations in which a hermit ("Der Ainsydel" [i.e. Einsiedler]) with crucifix (and sometimes beads) speaks to a figure representing one of the ten ages of human life, accompanied by an animal symbolic of that age. In this illustration we see a man of one hundred years, seated in a chair, holding his own beads and accompanied by a goose (symbolizing death -- like the goose for the table, the man will soon be food for worms). For a brief overview of this trope, see J.W. Jones, "Observations on the Origin of the Division of Man's Life into Stages," in Archaeologia 35 (1853), p. 167-189, especially p. 177-182. Woodcut illustration used by Hans Schobser of Munich. Established heading: Schobser, Hans,‏ ‎‡d d. 1530‏ Penn Libraries call number: GC5 G2733 516z All images from this book

Jones, "Observations on the Origin of the Division of Man's Life into Stages," in Archaeologia 35 (1853), p. 167-189, especially p. 177-182. Woodcut illustration used by Hans Schobser of Munich. photo.title: Vellum leaf from a liturgical music ms. (possibly an antiphonary?)
photo.description: Vellum leaf from a liturgical music ms. (possibly an antiphonary?), with 5-line staves in red and neumes and text in brown ink in a post-Gothic hand (not earlier than the 16th century, when the 5-line staff developed). The text appears to be an antiphon based on Song of Songs 7:10 and 3:4: "Ego dilecto meo et ad me conversio ejus; inveni quem diligit anima mea; tenui eum, nec dimittam." Following her canonization in 1728, this antiphon was sung with the Magnificat (the canticle for vespers) on the feast of St. Margaret of Cortona (23 February). Penn Libraries call number: GC5 G2733 510l All images from this book

photo.title: Woodcut illustration (used by Erhard Oeglin of Augsburg) of a banner bearer for the Bundschuh Insurrections (1493-1517), a series of German peasant revolts linked by their use of the imagery of a tied shoe
photo.description: Woodcut illustration (used by Erhard Oeglin of Augsburg) of a banner bearer for the Bundschuh Insurrections (1493-1517), a series of German peasant revolts linked by their use of the imagery of a tied shoe (Bundschuh, which can be seen on the ground at left). The bearer is possibly to be identified with Joss Fritz (ca. 1470-ca. 1525), who headed the 1513 insurrection in Lehen (now part of Freiburg im Breisgau) to which this work responds. The banner itself depicts Christ's crucifixion between the arms of Pope Julius II (right) and those of the Habsburg Holy Roman Emperors (left; effaced); this speaks to the first principle of Fritz's rebellion: "Erstens solle niemand mehr einen anderen Herrn als Gott, den Kaiser und den Papst anerkennen" [First, no one shall henceforth acknowledge any lord but God, the emperor, and the pope]. Established heading: Oeglin, Erhard, ‡d d. ca. 1520 Established heading: Fritz, Joss, ǂd ca. 1470-ca. 1525 Established heading: Bundschuh Insurrections, 1493-1517 Penn Libraries call number: GC5 G2733 510b

photo.title: Sir Stuart Alexander Donaldson, 1812-1867
photo.description: Motto: Aut pax aut bellum Very possibly Sir Stuart Alexander Donaldson (1812-1867), businessman, politician and the first Premier of the Colony of New South Wales. He was born in London, but emigrated to Sydney in 1835. After serving in several different political offices in Australia, he returned to England in 1859 and was knighted in 1860. Not to be confused with his eldest son, also Stuart Alexander Donaldson (1854-1915), Master of Magdalene College, Cambridge and Vice-chancellor of the University of Cambridge. Bookplate of John Arthur Brooke

John Arthur Brooke, of Fenay Hall, Huddersfield, West Riding, Yorkshire, England, b. 22 March 1844-d. 12 July 1920; m. 1873 Blanche Weston and had 4 children (Blanche, Dorothy, John Weston, and Robert Weston). Created Sir John Arthur Brooke, 1st Bart. Brooke of Almondbury, in 1919. An amateur ornithologist, he collected books on ornithology and natural history.

photo.title: Edith Anne Greene, d. 1912?
photo.description: Edith Anne Greene (d. 1912?; see below) was a notable designer of late 19th-century bookplates, particularly for women; cf. N. Labouchere, Ladies' Book-Plates (London: G. Bell & Sons, 1895), p. 168-171, and H.W. Fincham, Artists and Engravers of British and American Bookplates (London: Kegan Paul, Trench, Trübner & Co., 1897), p. 37. By 1895 she was a member of the Ex Libris Society and resident at 14 Royal Park, Clifton, Bristol, England; cf. W. Hamilton, Dated Book-Plates (London: A&C Black, 1895), p. 113. (K.E. Graf zu Leiningen-Westerburg also locates her in "Clifton Bristol" in his 1901 Deutsche und Oesterreichische Bibliothekzeichen Exlibris; cf. p. 558.) According to a solicitor's notice in The London Gazette 2 July 1912, a woman of that name resident at 15 Hanbury-road, Clifton, Bristol, died on 25 May 1912. This appears to be one of at least two bookplates she designed for herself; cf. J.F. Verster and W.H.K. Wright, "List of Landscape Bookplates" in Journal of the Ex Libris Society 10 (1900), p. 147. Penn Libraries call number: EC8 C6798 835s All images from this book
